  "root_text": {
    "sn11.16:0.1": "Saṁyutta Nikāya 11.16 ",
    "sn11.16:0.2": "2. Dutiyavagga ",
    "sn11.16:0.3": "Yajamānasutta ",
    "sn11.16:1.1": "Ekaṁ samayaṁ bhagavā rājagahe viharati gijjhakūṭe pabbate. ",
    "sn11.16:1.2": "Atha kho sakko devānamindo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṁ abhivādetvā ekamantaṁ aṭṭhāsi. ",
    "sn11.16:1.3": "Ekamantaṁ ṭhito kho sakko devānamindo bhagavantaṁ gāthāya ajjhabhāsi: ",
    "sn11.16:2.1": "“Yajamānānaṁ manussānaṁ, ",
    "sn11.16:2.2": "puññapekkhāna pāṇinaṁ; ",
    "sn11.16:2.3": "Karotaṁ opadhikaṁ puññaṁ, ",
    "sn11.16:2.4": "kattha dinnaṁ mahapphalan”ti. ",
    "sn11.16:3.1": "“Cattāro ca paṭipannā, ",
    "sn11.16:3.2": "cattāro ca phale ṭhitā; ",
    "sn11.16:3.3": "Esa saṅgho ujubhūto, ",
    "sn11.16:3.4": "paññāsīlasamāhito. ",
    "sn11.16:4.1": "Yajamānānaṁ manussānaṁ, ",
    "sn11.16:4.2": "Puññapekkhāna pāṇinaṁ; ",
    "sn11.16:4.3": "Karotaṁ opadhikaṁ puññaṁ, ",
    "sn11.16:4.4": "Saṅghe dinnaṁ mahapphalan”ti. "
  },
  "translation_text": {
    "sn11.16:0.1": "Linked Discourses 11.16 ",
    "sn11.16:0.2": "Chapter Two ",
    "sn11.16:0.3": "Sponsoring Sacrifice ",
    "sn11.16:1.1": "At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, on the Vulture’s Peak Mountain. ",
    "sn11.16:1.2": "And then Sakka, lord of gods, went up to the Buddha, bowed, stood to one side, ",
    "sn11.16:1.3": "and addressed him in verse: ",
    "sn11.16:2.1": "“For humans, those merit-seeking creatures, ",
    "sn11.16:2.2": "who sponsor sacrifices, ",
    "sn11.16:2.3": "making worldly merit, ",
    "sn11.16:2.4": "where is a gift very fruitful?” ",
    "sn11.16:3.1": "“Four practicing the path, ",
    "sn11.16:3.2": "and four established in the fruit. ",
    "sn11.16:3.3": "This is the upright Saṅgha, ",
    "sn11.16:3.4": "with wisdom, ethics, and immersion. ",
    "sn11.16:4.1": "For humans, those merit-seeking creatures, ",
    "sn11.16:4.2": "who sponsor sacrifices, ",
    "sn11.16:4.3": "making worldly merit, ",
    "sn11.16:4.4": "what is given to the Saṅgha is very fruitful.” "
  },
